# 2.1 Stochastic orders 

The quantile function for a random variable $X$ with distribution function $F_{X}$ is defined as:

$$
\operatorname{VaR}_{p}(X):=F_{X}^{-1}(p)=\inf \left\{x \in \mathbb{R} \mid F_{X}(x) \geq p\right\}, \quad p \in(0,1)
$$

Now, we present several pertinent definitions of univariate stochastic orders that will be utilized in subsequent discussions.

Definition 2.1. Let $X$ and $Y$ be two random variables with distribution functions $F_{X}$ and $F_{Y}$, density functions $f_{X}$ and $f_{Y}$, and survival functions $\bar{F}_{X}$ and $\bar{F}_{Y}$, respectively. Then $X$ is said to be smaller than $Y$ in the:
(i) usual stochastic order (denoted by $X \leq_{\mathrm{st}} Y$ ) if $\bar{F}_{X}(t) \leq \bar{F}_{Y}(t)$ for all $t \in \mathbb{R}$;
(ii) excess wealth order (denoted by $X \leq_{\mathrm{ew}} Y$ ) if $\mathbb{E}\left[\left(X-F_{X}^{-1}(p)\right)_{+}\right] \leq \mathbb{E}\left[\left(Y-F_{Y}^{-1}(p)\right)_{+}\right]$for all $0<p<1$, where $x_{+}=\max (0, x)$;
(iii) star order (denoted by $X \leq_{*} Y$ ) if $F_{Y}^{-1}(p) / F_{X}^{-1}(p)$ is increasing in $p \in(0,1)$, when the two random variables are non-negative;
(iv) expected proportional shortfall order (denoted by $X \leq_{\mathrm{ps}} Y$ ) if $\operatorname{EPS}_{p}(X) \leq \operatorname{EPS}_{p}(Y)$ for all $p \in$ $D_{X} \cap D_{Y}$, when the two random variables are non-negative, where $D_{X}=\left\{p \in(0,1): F_{X}^{-1}(p)>0\right\}$, $D_{Y}=\left\{p \in(0,1): F_{Y}^{-1}(p)>0\right\}$. Here,

$$
\operatorname{EPS}_{p}(X)=\mathbb{E}\left[\left(\frac{X-\operatorname{VaR}_{p}(X)}{\operatorname{VaR}_{p}(X)}\right)_{+}\right] \quad \text { and } \operatorname{EPS}_{p}(Y)=\mathbb{E}\left[\left(\frac{Y-\operatorname{VaR}_{p}(Y)}{\operatorname{VaR}_{p}(Y)}\right)_{+}\right]
$$

In Definition 2.1, (i)-(iii) are referenced in Shaked \& Shanthikumar (2007), and (iv) can be found in Belzunce et al. (2012). It is also known that both of the star order and the expected proportional shortfall order are scaled invariant and the former implies the latter. Interested readers can refer to the monographs Shaked \& Shanthikumar (2007) and Belzunce et al. (2015) for more detailed discussions.

Next, for the random vector $\boldsymbol{X}=\left(X_{1}, \ldots, X_{n}\right)$, we introduce some multivariate stochastic orders and dependence notions, indicating that in some stochastic sense, larger values of one random vector are associated with larger or smaller values of another random vector.

Definition 2.2. (Shaked \& Shanthikumar, 2007) Let $\boldsymbol{X}=\left(X_{1}, \ldots, X_{n}\right)$ and $\boldsymbol{Y}=\left(Y_{1}, \ldots, Y_{n}\right)$ be two random vectors with joint distribution functions $F$ and $G$, respectively. Then
(i) the random variable $\left\{X_{i}, i \in A^{c}\right\}$, is said to be right-tail increasing (decreasing) in $\left\{X_{j}, j \in A\right\}$, (denoted by $\left\{X_{i}, i \in A^{c}\right\} \uparrow_{\mathrm{RT}[\mathrm{RTD}]} \mid\left\{X_{j}, j \in A\right\}$ ) if $\mathbb{P}\left(X_{i}>x_{i}, i \in A^{c} \mid X_{j}>x_{j}, j \in A\right)$ increases (decreases) in $x_{j}$, where $A$ is a subset of $\{1, \ldots, n\}$ with at least one element, and $A^{c}$ denotes the complement of $A$;

(ii) the random vector $\boldsymbol{X}$ is said to be smaller than $\boldsymbol{Y}$ in the multivariate hazard rate order (denoted by $\boldsymbol{X} \leq_{\mathrm{hr}} \boldsymbol{Y}$ ) if $\bar{F}(\boldsymbol{x}) \bar{G}(\boldsymbol{y}) \leq \bar{F}(\boldsymbol{x} \wedge \boldsymbol{y}) \bar{G}(\boldsymbol{x} \vee \boldsymbol{y})$ for all $\boldsymbol{x}, \boldsymbol{y} \in \mathbb{R}^{n}$;
(iii) the random vector $\boldsymbol{X}$ is said to be smaller than $\boldsymbol{Y}$ in the weak multivariate hazard rate order (denoted by $\boldsymbol{X} \leq_{\mathrm{whr}} \boldsymbol{Y}$ ) if $\bar{G}(\boldsymbol{x}) / \bar{F}(\boldsymbol{x})$ is increasing in $\boldsymbol{x} \in\{\boldsymbol{x}: \bar{G}(\boldsymbol{x})>0\}$;
(iv) the random vector $\boldsymbol{X}$ is said to be smaller than $\boldsymbol{Y}$ in the usual stochastic order (denoted by $\boldsymbol{X} \leq_{\mathrm{st}} \boldsymbol{Y}$ ) if $\mathbb{E}[h(\boldsymbol{X})] \leq \mathbb{E}[h(\boldsymbol{Y})]$ for all bounded increasing $h: \mathbb{R}^{n} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$;
(v) the random vector $\boldsymbol{X}$ is said to be multivariate totally positive of order 2 (denoted by $\mathrm{MTP}_{2}$ ) if $f(\boldsymbol{x}) f(\boldsymbol{y}) \leq f(\boldsymbol{x} \wedge \boldsymbol{y}) f(\boldsymbol{x} \vee \boldsymbol{y})$ holds for all $\boldsymbol{x}, \boldsymbol{y} \in \mathbb{R}^{n}$;
(vi) the random vector $\boldsymbol{X}$ is said to be smaller than $\boldsymbol{Y}$ in the multivariate likelihood ratio order (denoted by $\boldsymbol{X} \leq_{\mathrm{lr}} \boldsymbol{Y}$ ) if $f(\boldsymbol{x}) g(\boldsymbol{y}) \leq f(\boldsymbol{x} \wedge \boldsymbol{y}) g(\boldsymbol{x} \vee \boldsymbol{y})$ for all $\boldsymbol{x}, \boldsymbol{y} \in \mathbb{R}^{n}$;
(vii) the random vector $\hat{\boldsymbol{X}}_{i}=\left(X_{1}, \ldots, X_{i-1}, X_{i+1}, \ldots, X_{n}\right)$ is said to be stochastically increasing in $X_{i}$ (denoted by $\hat{\boldsymbol{X}}_{i} \uparrow_{\mathrm{SI}} X_{i}$ ) if the conditional distribution $\left\{\left(X_{1}, \ldots, X_{i-1}, X_{i+1}, \ldots, X_{n} \mid X_{i}=x_{i}\right)\right\}$ is stochatically increasing as $x_{i}$ increases;
(viii) the random vector $\boldsymbol{X}$ is said to be positive dependent through the stochastic order (or PDS) if $\hat{\boldsymbol{X}}_{i} \uparrow_{\mathrm{SI}} X_{i}$ for $i \in\{1, \ldots, n\}$.

According to Hu et al. (2003), the following relationships hold:

$$
\boldsymbol{X} \leq_{\mathrm{lr}} \boldsymbol{Y} \Longrightarrow \boldsymbol{X} \leq_{\mathrm{lr}} \boldsymbol{Y} \Longrightarrow \boldsymbol{X} \leq_{\mathrm{whr}} \boldsymbol{Y} \text { and } \boldsymbol{X} \leq_{\mathrm{lr}} \boldsymbol{Y} \Longrightarrow \boldsymbol{X} \leq_{\mathrm{st}} \boldsymbol{Y}
$$

# 4.2 Parameter estimation of the mixed copula 

As per Table 2, it can be noted that the correlation coefficients between cryptocurrencies pairs are different, indicating that the interdependence among cryptocurrencies is significantly asymmetric. Hence, the dependence structure between these cryptocurrencies cannot be characterized by symmetric copulas. Besides, Figure 6 shows that any pair of these three cryptocurrencies have a strong positive dependence at extreme values (for both of the left and right tails). Take these observations into consideration, we ought to use an asymmetric copula with non-zero left and right tail dependence coefficients to model the dependence structure between these cryptocurrencies. As a result, we employ a mixed copula model to characterize the dependence structure. The mixed copula model is widely used in the existing literature, like Cai \& Wang (2014) and Zhu et al. (2023).

We use the mixed Copula model

$$
C^{M}(\boldsymbol{u})=a_{1} C^{G a u}(\boldsymbol{u})+a_{2} C^{G u m}(\boldsymbol{u})+\left(1-a_{1}-a_{2}\right) C^{C l a}(\boldsymbol{u}), \quad 0 \leq a_{1}, a_{2} \leq 1, \quad a_{1}+a_{2} \leq 1, \quad \boldsymbol{u} \in[0,1]^{3}
$$

as the dependency model, where the Gaussian copula is used to capture the correlation between variables, the Gumbel copula models upper tail dependence, and the Clayton copula models lower tail dependence.

